Officers confronted a male suspect after shots were fired on High Street North. This is located in the London borough of Newham. Officers responded to calls in the evening on Saturday. They were unarmed. The air rifle is understood to have been discharged both inside an address and into the high street. After the suspect was confronted, he was arrested. The air rifle has since been recovered by forces. The Newham branch of the Metropolitan Police reported on the crime in a post on Twitter just after 9pm. It described the conduct of the officers as “brave”. The branch said: “Unarmed officers bravely confronted the male suspect and arrested him. “One air rifle has been recovered.” One pedestrian received injuries during the incident. The Met described the injuries as “minor”. READ MORE: Britons blast Tories and Labour who are ‘as bad as each other’ In its most recent Violence Suppression Unit newsletter, Newham MPS revealed it conducted 32 arrests in April. It also stopped and searched 99 potential suspects. On its aims for this month, May, it said: “We will be concentrating on those offenders that carry weapons.” It added it would also focus on “reducing robberies and tackling violent crime”. Express.co.uk approached the Metropolitan Police for more details. DON'T MISS: Boris urged to cut the ‘soundbites’ and focus on action [OPINION] Tory civil war erupts as Scottish Conservatives REFUSE to back Boris [REPORT] Prince Andrew legal settlement with Giuffre 'will have been millions' [REVEAL]